<BLOCK1><TI>REPLY TO THE NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>In reply to the Appellant's Notice of Appeal in the matter of section 85 of the <EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. C.40, as amended (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>CTA</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), for the taxation year ending on January 2, 2008 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2008 Year</BOLD>&rdquo;), the Attorney General of Canada (&ldquo;<BOLD>AGC</BOLD>&rdquo;) says:</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The AGC admits the allegations of fact contained in paragraphs 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12, 16 and 17 of the Notice of Appeal.</P>
<P>2. The AGC denies the allegations of fact contained in paragraph 15 of the Notice of Appeal.</P>
<P>3. In respect of paragraph 6 of the Notice of Appeal, the AGC denies that the tax returns for the 2010 Taxation Year were filed on June 30, 2010 and says that they were filed on June 25, 2010. The AGC admits the other allegation of fact contained in that paragraph.</P>
<P>4. In respect of paragraph 11 of the Notice of Appeal, the AGC admits that the Appellant objected to the Federal Reassessments, but says that the Appellant did so on September 24, 2013.</P>
<P>5. In respect of paragraph 13 of the Notice of Appeal, the AGC says that the objections were allowed in part and admits the other allegations of fact contained in that paragraph.</P>
<P>6. The AGC admits that the allegations of fact contained in paragraph 14 of the Notice of Appeal, but says that the amount of tax payable admitted is not the amount of tax payable for the purposes of ss. 79(7) and 82(5) of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P>
<P>7. The AGC denies all other allegations of fact contained in the Notice of Appeal.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Respondent's assumptions</TI>
<P>8. In determining the Appellant's liability to tax for the 2008 Year, the Respondent made the assumptions of fact set out below in paragraphs 9 through 34.</P>
<P>9. On June 12, 2008, the Respondent first assessed the Appellant under the <EM>CTA</EM> for the 2008 Year for income tax payable of $4,050,980 and capital tax payable of $41,802.</P>
<P>10. On December 8, 2008, the Respondent reassessed the Appellant under the <EM>CTA</EM> for the 2008 Year to reduce capital tax payable to $33,002.</P>
<P>11. On June 25, 2010, the Appellant filed a corporate tax return for both federal and Ontario purposes for its taxation year ended January 2, 2010 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2010 Year</BOLD>&rdquo;), reporting a loss of $14,498,947.</P>
<P>12. On the same date, the Appellant requested that part of this non-capital loss, in the amount of $4,000,000 be carried back to its 2008 Year (&ldquo;<BOLD>Loss Carryback</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>13. The Minister of National Revenue (&ldquo;<BOLD>Federal Minister</BOLD>&rdquo;) assessed the Appellant's tax liability for the 2010 under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, RSC 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.)(&ldquo;<BOLD>Federal Act</BOLD>&rdquo;) as filed.</P>
<P>14. The Federal Minister also allowed the Appellant's request for the Loss Carryback. Accordingly, the Federal Minister reassessed the Appellant for the 2008 Year to allow the deduction of the Loss Carryback in computing the Appellant's taxable income for that year under the Federal Act.</P>
<P>15. Notice of this federal reassessment for the 2008 Year was dated September 16, 2010 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2010 Federal Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>16. As a result of the 2010 Federal Reassessment, the Respondent also reassessed the Appellant under the <EM>CTA</EM> for the 2008 Year to allow the deduction of the Loss Carryback in computing the Appellant's taxable income for that year.</P>
<P>17. Notice of this reassessment was dated November 24, 2010 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2010 Ontario Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>18. This 2010 Ontario Reassessment resulted in a reduction of the Appellant's income tax payable for the 2008 Year and a refund of $560,000 to the Appellant on December 19, 2010 with no interest.</P>
<P>19. The Federal Minister later reassessed the Appellant's tax liability under the Federal Act, reversing the previously allowed Loss Carryback in its entirety.</P>
<P>20. Notice of this federal reassessment was dated July 3, 2013 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2013 Federal Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>21. Following the 2013 Federal Reassessment, the Respondent reassessed the Appellant's tax liability under the <EM>CTA</EM> for the 2008 Year to reverse the previously allowed Loss Carryback in its entirety.</P>
<P>22. Notice of this reassessment was dated July 22, 2013 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2013 Ontario Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>23. The 2013 Ontario Reassessment was a designated assessment within the meaning of s. 92 of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P>
<P>24. The 2013 Ontario Reassessment reinstated the income tax payable of $560,000 that the Respondent had previously refunded to the Appellant.</P>
<P>25. Under the 2013 Ontario Reassessment for the 2008 Year:
<P1>a) the Appellant had capital tax payable of $33,002;</P1>
<P1>b) the Appellant was denied the deduction in computing taxable income of the Loss Carryback in the amount of $4,000,000;</P1>
<P1>c) the Appellant had taxable income of $28,959,711;</P1>
<P1>d) the Appellant had income tax payable of $4,054,360; and,</P1>
<P1>e) the Appellant had total tax payable of $4,087,362 (<EM>i.e.</EM>, income tax payable of $4,054,360 + capital tax payable of $33,002).</P1></P>
<P>26. On October 11, 2013, the Appellant made a payment of $668,801.75 to the Respondent, which was payment of this $560,000 in tax payable plus $104,601.75 in additional interest charged.</P>
<P>27. The Appellant did not object to the 2013 Ontario Reassessment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The Appellant was not required to object. As the Appellant chose not to object to this designated assessment, but did object to the 2013 Federal Reassessment, then both the Appellant and the Respondent were bound by the Federal Minister's decision on the 2013 Federal Reassessment in accordance with s. 92(2) of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. On September 24, 2013, the Appellant objected to the 2013 Federal Reassessment.</P>
<P>29. In response to the objection, the Federal Minister reassessed the Appellant's tax liability under the Federal Act to reinstate the Loss Carryback in its entirety.</P>
<P>30. Notice of this federal reassessment was dated August 14, 2015 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2015 Federal Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>31. Following the 2015 Federal Reassessment, the Respondent reassessed the Appellant's tax liability under the <EM>CTA</EM> for the 2008 Year to reinstate the Loss Carryback in its entirety.</P>
<P>32. Notice of this reassessment was dated September 22, 2015 (&ldquo;<BOLD>2015 Ontario Reassessment</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>33. Under the 2015 Ontario Reassessment, the Respondent allowed the Loss Carryback and, as a result, the Appellant had total tax payable of $3,527,362 ($3,494,360 in income tax payable and $33,002 in capital tax payable).</P>
<P>34. The 2015 Ontario Reassessment resulted in a refund to the Appellant of $663,128.84.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>ISSUE TO BE DECIDED</TI>
<P>35. The issues are:
<P1>a) whether the Appellant is entitled to an enhanced rate of interest on the refund in respect of its 2008 Year, and</P1>
<P1>b) if the Appellant is so entitled, whether it is also entitled to pre&mdash;and post-judgment interest under ss. 128 and 129 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. C.43.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>STATUTORY PROVISIONS, GROUNDS RELIED ON, AND RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>36. The AGC relies on ss. 1(1), 34(1), 79(7), 80, 82 and 92 of the <EM>CTA</EM>, s. 503 of RRO 1990, Reg. 183 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Regulations</BOLD>&rdquo;) and ss. 111 and 248(1) (definition of &ldquo;assessment&rdquo;) of the Federal Act.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>No entitlement to an enhanced rate of interest</TI>
<P>37. The Respondent correctly calculated the interest payable to the Appellant. The Appellant was not entitled to the enhanced rate of interest prescribed for the purposes of s. 82(5) of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P>
<P>38. Generally speaking, pursuant to ss. 503(2)4 and 4.1 of the Regulations, where the Respondent must pay interest to a corporation, it pays interest at amount that is less than the &ldquo;base rate&rdquo;, the base rate being a rate based on an average prime rate.</P>
<P>39. However, under s. 82(5) of the <EM>CTA</EM>, the Respondent must pay an enhanced rate of interest&mdash;the relevant base rate&mdash;where:
<P1>a) the corporation objects to a reassessment for a particular taxation year;</P1>
<P1>b) it is finally determined that the corporation's tax payable for that year is less than the amount assessed under s. 80 of the <EM>CTA</EM>; and,</P1>
<P1>c) as a result, either:
<P2>(i) a surplus, as defined in s. 82(7) of the <EM>CTA</EM>, in the corporation's tax account arises for the particular taxation year, or,</P2>
<P2>(ii) a surplus, as defined in s. 83(2) of the <EM>CTA</EM>, arises in the corporation's instalment account for the particular taxation year.</P2></P1></P>
<P>40. The enhanced interest rate is prescribed for the purposes of s. 82(5) in s. 503(2)5 of the Regulations. It applies only to the surplus attributable to the determination made on the objection.</P>
<P>41. The corporation's tax account represents the balance of any unpaid amounts (tax or other amounts such as penalties) or overpayments relating to a taxation year, as adjusted for interest.</P>
<P>42. The corporation's instalment account measures whether a corporation has unpaid, underpaid, or overpaid instalments of tax at any particular time during the instalment period. The instalment period starts on the first day of the taxation year and ends on the day which is the earlier of the date of the most current assessment or reassessment for the year, and the day before the balance of tax is due for the year, as required by s. 78(2) of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P>
<P>43. For the purposes of computing interest under s. 82(5), the tax payable by the corporation is deemed to be the amount determined as if a loss carried back from a subsequent taxation year had not been deducted. This deeming rule is found in s. 79(7) of the <EM>CTA</EM>.</P>
<P>44. Although the Appellant was successful in objecting to the 2013 Federal Reassessment (which successful objection applied to the 2013 Ontario Reassessment), it cannot benefit from the enhanced interest rate under s. 82(5). The objection did not result in a decision that reduced the Appellant's tax payable, as deemed by s. 79(7) of the <EM>CTA</EM>, to an amount that was less than the amount assessed under the 2013 Ontario Reassessment. For the purpose of calculating interest under s. 82(5):
<P1>a) under the 2013 Ontario Reassessment, the Respondent reassessed the Appellant total tax payable of $4,088,182 (i.e., income tax payable of $4,087,362 + capital tax payable of $33,002) for the 2008 Year, and</P1>
<P1>b) following its objection to the 2013 Federal Reassessment, and as a result of the 2015 Ontario Reassessment, the Appellant still had the same total tax payable of $4,088,182 for the 2008 Year. To reiterate, under s. 79(7), the Loss Carryback did not reduce the total tax payable for the purposes of calculating interest under s. 82(5).</P1></P>
<P>45. For the purpose of calculating interest, then, there is no difference between the amount assessed by the Respondent and the amount of tax payable resulting from the resolution of the objection. Subsection 82(5), with its enhanced rate of interest, does not apply.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>No entitlement to pre- and post-judgment interest under the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM></TI>
<P>46. If the Appellant is successful on its appeal to this Court, it is not entitled to pre&mdash;and post-judgment interest under ss. 128 and 129 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>. The <EM>CTA</EM> would itself provide for interest. Pursuant to ss. 128(4)(g) and 129(4), neither ss. 128 or 129 would have any application.</P>
<P>The AGC requests that the appeal be dismissed with costs.</P>
