<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. Paragraph 79(7)(a) of the <EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM> provides that, for the purposes of calculating interest to be allowed to a corporation under s. 82, tax payable is deemed to be the amount of tax payable without taking into account a loss carried back to that year from a later year.</P>
<P>2. Subsection 82(5) provides for the use of an enhanced interest rate where the corporation successfully objects to, or appeals from, an assessment. The enhanced interest rate is applied, more precisely, where the tax payable from the successful objection or appeal is less than the tax payable as assessed by the Minister.</P>
<P>3. The Appellant objected to a reassessment denying it a loss carryback. The Appellant's objection was successful and the Minister allowed the loss carryback. However, the Appellant cannot benefit from the enhanced rate of interest.</P>
<P>4. The deeming definition of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) applies to s. 82(5) because s. 82(5) is integral to the mathematical procedure for calculating of interest under the Act. As a result of the application of s. 79(7)(a), there was no difference between the tax payable as reassessed by the Minister before the objection and the tax payable as reassessed by the Minister after the objection.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">I. FACTS</TI>
<P>5. The facts are set out in the Agreed Statement of Facts. It is useful to highlight certain of them:
<P1>a) The Appellant carried a non-capital loss of $4 million back from the taxation year ended January 2, 2010 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>2010 Year</BOLD>&rdquo;) to the taxation year ended January 2, 2008 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>2008 Year</BOLD>&rdquo;), the year under appeal for federal purposes under the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RSC 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> supp.).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<BOLD>Federal Act</BOLD>&rdquo;) and for provincial purposes under the <EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RSO 1990, c. C.40, as it read at the time.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;<BOLD>CTA</BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Agreed Statement of Facts, para 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b) Following a federal reassessment of the 2008 Year denying the loss carryback, the Minister<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Responsibility for the administration of the CTA has been assigned to either of the Minister of Finance or the Minister of Revenue over the years. The reference to Minister will refer to the relevant minister at any given time.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> reassessed the Appellant under the CTA and denied this loss carryback of $4 million.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Agreed Statement of Facts, paras 8-9 and Appendix B.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>c) The Appellant objected to the federal reassessment. Ultimately, the Appellant was successful on the federal objection and the non-capital loss carryback of $4 million was reinstated for federal purposes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Agreed Statement of Facts, paras 10, 12 and 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>d) The Minister was bound by this result. He reassessed the Appellant to reinstate the non-capital loss carryback of $4 million for Ontario purposes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Agreed Statement of Facts, para 14 and Appendix C. Because the Ontario reassessment was designated under s. 92 of the CTA, the Appellant was not required to object to the Ontario reassessment if it objected to the related federal reassessment. Both the Minister and the Appellant were bound by the resolution of the related federal reassessment.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>e) As a result of this reassessment, the Minister issued a refund to the Appellant, without refund interest.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts, para 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>6. The Minister did not allow the Appellant the enhanced interest rate under s. 82(5) of the CTA. However, the Minister did give credit interest to the Appellant. This credit interest is shown on the face of the notice of reassessment found at Appendix C of the Agreed Statement of Facts.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">II. POINT IN ISSUE</TI>
<P>7. The question posed by the Appellant in its Notice of Motion is:
<QUOTE><P>Whether, in determining a corporation's entitlement to an enhanced refund interest rate under subsection 82(5) of the [CTA], <EM>tax payable</EM> must take a deduction from a loss carried back into account ...</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. The question can be put another way: does the deemed definition of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) apply to s. 82(5) of the CTA?</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">III. SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>THE ENHANCED RATE OF INTEREST DOES NOT APPLY TO THE SURPLUS IN THE APPELLANT'S TAX ACCOUNT</TI>
<P>9. The deemed definition of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) applies to s. 82(5) of the CTA. As a result, the Appellant cannot benefit from the enhanced interest rate under s. 82(5).</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>STATUTORY INTERPRETATION OF S. 79(7)(a)</TI>
<P>10. In determining whether the deemed definition of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) applies to s. 82(5), the Court considers the text, context and purpose of s. 79(7)(a). Where the words of the text are clear, they should be given predominance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Trustco Mortgage Co v Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 54</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2005] 2 SCR 601</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. <CASEREF><SOC>Rizzo &amp; Rizzo Shoes Ltd (Re)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 SCR 27</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Policy concerns cannot be used to disregard the clear meaning of those words.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>R v Cheema</SOC><CITE>2018 FCA 45</CITE><PARANUM>71&ndash;86</PARANUM></CASEREF>, per Stratas J.A. (leave to appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada refused).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>THE TEXT SHOW THAT THE DEFINITION OF TAX PAYABLE IN S. 79(7)(a) APPLIES WHERE ANY PART OF SS. 79, 82 OR 83 IS FOR THE PURPOSES OF CALCULATING INTEREST</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>1)</N><TI>The text of s. 79(7) of the CTA</TI>
<P>11. Subsection 79(7) provides two deeming rules to deal with, among other things, the impact of a loss on the calculation of interest for the taxation year to which the loss is carried back. It reads as follows:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(7)</N><TI>Effect of loss carried back</TI><SSECP>For the purposes of calculating interest payable or allowed under this section or section 82 or 83 in respect of a particular taxation year, and for the purpose of determining the amount of a penalty, if any, to be assessed under subsection 76 (1) or (2) and the amount of tax payable under subsections 78 (4) and (6),
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the tax payable by the corporation under this Act for a taxation year shall be deemed to be the amount that would otherwise be determined if all amounts deducted by the corporation for that year under section 111 of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada), as it applies for the purposes of this Act, in respect of a loss for a taxation year after the particular year (in this section referred to as the &ldquo;loss year&rdquo;) were not deducted; and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the amount, if any, by which the tax payable by the corporation under this Act for the particular taxation year is reduced as a result of a deduction referred to in clause (a) shall be deemed to be an amount paid by the corporation on account of its liability under this Act for the particular year on the day that is the latest of,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>the first day of the taxation year after the loss year,</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(ii)</N><SPARAP>the day on which the corporation's return for the loss year is delivered to the Minister, or</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(iii)</N><SPARAP>the day on which the Minister receives a request in writing from the corporation to reassess the particular taxation year to take into account the deduction referred to in clause (a).</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. Subsection 111(1) of the Federal Act, which is made applicable to the CTA pursuant to s. 34(1) of that Act,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Subsection 34(1) more precisely makes Division C of Part I of the Federal Act apply. Section 111 of the Federal Act is in that Division.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> allows a corporation to carry back and deduct in computing its taxable income a number of kinds of losses (from the loss year) to an earlier taxation year.</P>
<P>13. Here, the Appellant carried back a non-capital loss. Paragraph 111(1)(a) of the Federal Act allows the corporation to carry back a non-capital loss to any of the three preceding taxation years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The term, &ldquo;non-capital loss&rdquo;, is defined in s. 111(8) of the Federal Act. corporation's loss from various sources, including business or property.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. Subject to certain restrictions contained in the Federal Act, only the corporation may choose the year to which it will apply the non-capital loss.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>CCLI (1994) Inc v Canada</SOC><CITE>2007 FCA 185</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. The ultimate effect of s. 111(1) of the Federal Act is that by allowing the corporation to reduce its taxable income by carrying back a non-capital loss, it also allows the corporation to reduce its tax payable for the year.</P>
<P>16. Under s. 79(7)(a), this reduction of tax payable is not permitted for interest and penalty calculation purposes, as well as for certain payments (this refers to ss. 78(4) and (6)). Paragraph 79(7)(a) deems the tax payable for the year to which the loss is carried back to be the corporation's tax payable as if it had <BOLD>not</BOLD> been reduced by the loss carryback.</P>
<P>17. Paragraph 79(7)(b) deems the amount by which the tax payable of a corporation would otherwise be reduced by the loss carryback to be an amount <BOLD>paid</BOLD> toward tax payable for the year to which the loss is carried back only on the latest of the three dates set out in that paragraph. The latest of these three dates is known as the effective interest date.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2)</N><TI>For certain purposes, the deemed meaning of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) prevails over the general definition of tax payable in s. 1(1)(d) of the CTA</TI>
<P>18. Subsection 79(7) provides its own deemed definition of tax payable. However, there is already a general definition of tax payable in s. 1(1)(d) of the CTA. Paragraph 1(1)(d) reads in part as follows:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>1.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In this Act and in the application of the provisions of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada) that are by this Act made applicable for the purposes of this Act,
<PARA><N>(d)</N><PARAP>the interpretations contained in the said Part XVII of the expressions ... &ldquo;tax payable&rdquo; do not apply and in lieu thereof the following interpretations are applicable:
<QUOTE><P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>&ldquo;tax payable&rdquo;, by a corporation or other person under any Part of this Act by or under which provision is made for the assessment of tax, means the tax payable by the corporation or other person as fixed by assessment or reassessment, subject to variation on objection or appeal, if any, in accordance with sections 84 to 92, (&ldquo;imp&oc;t payable&rdquo;)</P></QUOTE></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. Where two provisions are in conflict, the conflict may be avoided by applying the more specific provision instead of the general provision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>National Bank Life Insurance, Life Insurance Co v R</SOC><CITE>2006 FCA 161</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. Paragraph 79(7)(a) is more specific than s. 1(1)(d). It applies for limited purposes, among them, for &ldquo;the purposes of calculating interest&rdquo; under ss. 79, 82 and 83 in their entirety&mdash;including s. 82(5). It is therefore necessary to understand the phrase &ldquo;for the purposes of calculating interest&rdquo;.</P>
<P>21. The phrase &ldquo;for the purposes of calculating interest&rdquo; is not defined in the CTA. The dictionary meaning of the verb &ldquo;calculate&rdquo;, is:
<QUOTE><P>Subject: Science and technology, Mathematics and Computer Science To work out the value of a mathematical or arithmetical procedure, or the output of an algorithm.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Katherine Barber, ed, <EM>Canadian Oxford Dictionary</EM>, 2d ed (Oxford University Press, 2005) (accessed May 14, 2019).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>22. The mathematical procedure for calculating interest involves multiplying (1) a principal amount by (2) an interest rate over (3) a time period.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>3)</N><TI>Conclusion on text</TI>
<P>23. The text of s. 79(7) shows that this subsection is specific to the treatment of loss carrybacks in the calculation of interest. This text does not restrict the application of s. 79(7) to any particular step in, or element of, the mathematical procedure for working out an amount of interest. To the extent that ss. 79, 82 and 83 provide for any step in, or element of, this mathematical procedure, they are for the purposes of calculating interest.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>THE CONTEXT SHOWS THAT EACH PART OF SS. 79, 82 AND 83 THAT IS INTEGRAL TO THE CALCULATION OF INTEREST IS FOR THE PURPOSES OF CALCULATING INTEREST</TI>
<P>24. In the context in which s. 79(7) is found, a provision is for the purposes of calculating interest without setting out the entire mathematical procedure for doing so. No one part of ss. 79, 82 or 83 set out the entire mathematical procedure for working out an amount of interest. However, most of the provisions in these sections are integral to this procedure. Each provision that is integral to this procedure must be for the purposes of calculating interest.</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1)</N><TI>Interest payable and interest allowed to a corporation under the CTA</TI>
<P>25. Subsection 79(7)'s immediate context is the framework under the CTA for calculating interest payable by or allowable to a corporation.</P>
<BLOCK5><N>a)</N><TI>Interest on surpluses and deficiencies in a corporation's instalment and tax accounts</TI>
<P>26. Section 79 deals in large part with interest payable by a corporation. Sections 82 and 83 deal in large part with interest allowable by the Minister.</P>
<P>27. In broad terms, who owes interest for any given day depends on whether the corporation has a surplus or deficiency on that day in one of two accounts: the instalment account and the tax account.</P>
<P>28. During the course of a taxation year, the corporation must pay instalments of tax payable for the year: s. 78(2)(a).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The instalments are based on the tax payable for the year, the tax payable for the previous year (called the first instalment base), or the tax payable two years before (called the second instalment base): s. 78(2)(b). The first and second instalment bases are defined in ss. 507(1) and (2) of RRO 1990, Reg. 183. Under s. 507(12) of these Regulations, which operates in much the same way as s. 79(7)(a), the tax payable that forms the instalment base does not take into account the loss carryback.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The amounts owing as instalments of tax payable and any interest on those instalments, less any amounts paid or credited or deemed to have been paid or credited to the amounts owing, are tracked in the corporation's instalment account. If the corporation owes more than it has paid or has had credited toward the amounts it owes, it has a deficiency in its instalment account: s. 79(4.1). If the corporation has paid or has been credited with more than it owes, then there is a surplus in its instalment account: s. 83(2).</P>
<P>29. For any day on which there is a deficiency in the account, the corporation must pay interest: s. 79(4). For any day on which there is a surplus in the account, the Minister must allow interest: s. 83(1).</P>
<P>30. At the end of a taxation year (more precisely, depending on the circumstances, either on or before the end of the second or third month following the year: s. 78(2)(b)), the corporation must pay the balance of its tax payable for the year.</P>
<P>31. The amounts owing as tax payable, penalties and interest, less any amounts paid or credited to those amounts, are tracked in the corporation's tax account. If the corporation owes more than it has paid or had credited to the amounts it owes, it has a deficiency in its tax account: s. 79(2). If the corporation has paid or has been credited with more than it owes, then there is a surplus in the tax account: s. 82(7).</P>
<P>32. For any day on which there is a deficiency in the account, the corporation must pay interest: s. 79(1). For any day on which there is a surplus in the account, the Minister must allow interest.</P>
<P>33. The general rule for the allowance of interest by the Minister is set out in s. 82(4):
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(4)</N><TI>Interest allowed</TI><SSECP>Interest at the rate prescribed by the regulations shall be calculated and allowed daily to a corporation on the surplus in the corporation's tax account for a taxation year, for each day there is a surplus in the tax account after the end of the instalment period for the taxation year.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. The enhanced interest rate is provided through s. 82(5). This subsection reads as follows:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(5)</N><TI>Interest, after objection or appeal</TI><SSECP>Where, by a decision made under section 84 or 92 or by a court, it is finally determined that the tax payable under this Act by a corporation for a taxation year is less than the amount assessed<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pursuant to s. 1(1)(a) of the CTA, s. 248(1) of the Federal Act generally applies. Under the s. 248(1) definition of assessment, an assessment includes a reassessment.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> under section 80 to which the objection was made or from which the appeal was taken, and as a result of the decision there is a surplus in the corporation's tax account for a taxation year or in the corporation's instalment account for a taxation year, the interest rate prescribed by the regulations for the purposes of this subsection, and not the rate prescribed for the purposes of subsection (4) or 83 (1), as the case may be, shall be used to determine the amount of interest for the purposes of those subsections, for each day that the surplus in the account is attributable to the decision.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>b)</N><TI>The prescribed interest rates</TI>
<P>35. Interest rates are prescribed in RRO 1990, Reg. 183, s. 503. Interest rates are adjusted on a quarterly basis, on the adjustment date: s. 503(1). The base rate of interest is the average prime rate at a particular point in time: s. 503(2). The rates are as follows:
<P1>a) 3% higher than the base rate, when the corporation must pay interest: s. 503(2)3;</P1>
<P1>b) 3% lower than the base rate when the Minister must allow interest and s. 82(5) does not apply: s. 503(2)4.1; and</P1>
<P1>c) the base rate itself, when the Minister must allow interest and s. 82(5) applies: s. 503(2)5. This is called the enhanced rate of interest in the Appellant's materials.</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>c)</N><TI>The mathematical procedure under the CTA for calculating interest</TI>
<P>36. Given the framework set out above for the calculation of interest payable or allowable to a corporation under the CTA, in broad terms, the mathematical procedure for calculating interest payable or allowable under the CTA consists of the following steps:
<P1>a) determine the principal amount on which interest accrues&mdash;<EM>i.e.</EM>, determine whether there is a surplus or deficiency on a given day, which requires:
<P2>i) determining the tax payable for the taxation year;</P2>
<P2>ii) determining any other amount payable by the corporation (<EM>e.g.</EM>, interest and penalties);</P2>
<P2>iii) determining the amounts paid by, credited to, or deemed to have been paid or credited to the corporation; and</P2>
<P2>iv) determining the interest allowed to the corporation;</P2></P1>
<P1>b) determine the applicable interest rate; and</P1>
<P1>c) multiply the surplus or deficiency on the given day by the applicable interest rate.</P1></P>
<P>37. The same approach, with slight modifications, applies to the calculation of interest on a deficiency or surplus in the instalment account.</P>
<P>38. Where there is an objection or appeal, s. 82(5) provides (a) in part, as well as (b) and (c) of the mathematical procedure for calculating interest on the surpluses in tax and instalment accounts.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2)</N><TI>No part of ss. 79, 82 and 83 supplies the complete mathematical procedure under the CTA for calculating interest</TI>
<P>39. No part of ss. 79, 82 or 83 sets out this entire mathematical procedure for calculating interest. Most of the provisions in these sections are, however, integral to the procedure. If the Legislature wanted to target only parts of ss. 79, 82 and 83, it could have done so. If the Legislature wanted to limit the application of s. 79(7)(a) to only the part of s. 82 that contained a mathematical procedure that calculated interest at the general rate, it would have been easy enough to target s. 82(4). Until 1994, the Legislature <BOLD>did</BOLD> target s. 82(4) (and its predecessors) in s. 79(7) (and its predecessors).</P>
<BLOCK5><N>a)</N><TI>Section 79</TI>
<P>40. Section 79 contains subsections that refer to the calculation of interest. Subsection 79(1) reads in part: &ldquo;Interest ... shall be calculated and charged daily and be payable by a corporation ...&rdquo; Subsection 79(4) reads in part: &ldquo;... the corporation is liable to pay interest ... calculated and charged daily on ...&rdquo; Subsection (4.01) contains the same language as subsection (4).</P>
<P>41. None of these subsections is sufficient in and of itself to calculate an amount of interest.</P>
<P>42. Take s. 79(1). It tells us which interest rate to apply to a deficiency in the tax account over a particular period (each day). Subsection 79(1) does not tell us how to calculate the deficiency. We need to look at s. 79(2). Other subsections define elements of the deficiency calculation (e.g., s. 79(3)&ndash;(3.2), (10)) or limit the interest payables by a corporation (s. 79(9)). No part of s. 79 provides the entire mathematical procedure for calculating interest payable by the corporation. All parts of s. 79 are integral to this procedure.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>b)</N><TI>Section 82</TI>
<P>43. Unlike s. 79, some parts of s. 82 have no bearing on the mathematical procedure for calculating interest. Subsections 82(1), (2), (3), (8) and (11) relate to the refund or other application of overpayments. While interest payable by or allowable to a corporation under ss. 79(1) and 82(4) or (5) is included in the calculation of an overpayment, ss. 82(1), (2), (3), (8) and (11) do not themselves provide any element of the interest calculation. These subsections cannot be for the purposes of calculating interest.</P>
<P>44. Only one subsection in s. 82 uses any variation of the word &ldquo;calculate&rdquo;: This is s. 82(4) itself: &ldquo;Interest ... shall be calculated at the rate prescribed by regulations ...&rdquo;</P>
<P>45. Putting aside s. 82(5) for the moment, the rest of s. 82 provides <BOLD>parts</BOLD> of the mathematical procedure for calculating interest. Subsection 82(4) tells us that the general interest rate applies to a surplus in the tax account over a particular period (daily). This subsection does not tell us what the interest rate is. For this, we need to look at s. 503(5) of the Regulations.</P>
<P>46. Subsection 82(1) also does not tell us how to calculate the surplus. We need to look at s. 82(7). And, to calculate the surplus, s. 82(7) takes us to ss. 79(2)(a) and (b). There are also other subsections that tell us the first day on which interest on a surplus becomes allowable (s. 83(6)) or that limits the total interest allowable over a certain period (s. 83(9)-(10)). Each of these subsections is integral to the calculation of interest, but none of them is sufficient to calculate this interest.</P>
<P>47. Taking s. 82(5) into account, in certain circumstances, this subsection tells us that a different interest rate may apply and that this interest rate applies only to the surplus in the tax account attributed to a decision on an objection or appeal. It also uses language similar to that of s. 82(4) without using a variation of the word calculate: &ldquo;... the interest rate prescribed by the regulations ... shall be used to determine the amount of interest ...&rdquo; It is also integral to the calculation of interest.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>c)</N><TI>Section 83</TI>
<P>48. No part of s. 83 provides the entire mathematical procedure for calculating interest. No part even uses a variation of the word &ldquo;calculate&rdquo;. Subsection 83(1) provides: &ldquo;Interest ... shall be computed ...&rdquo; Putting aside s. 82(5), s. 83(1) tells us that a particular interest rate applies to a surplus in the instalment account over a particular period (each day). This subsection does not tell us what the interest rate is. For this, we need to look at s. 503(5) of the Regulations. Subsection 83(1) also does not tell us how to calculate the surplus. We need to look at s. 83(2). And, to calculate the surplus, s. 83(2) takes us to ss. 79(4.1)(a) and (b). Each of these subsections is integral to the calculation of interest, but none of them is sufficient to calculate this interest.</P>
<P>49. Taking s. 82(5) into account, in certain circumstances, this subsection tells us that a different interest rate may apply and that this interest rate applies only to the surplus in the instalment account attributed to a decision on an objection or appeal.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>3)</N><TI>Paragraph 79(7)(a)'s deemed definition works only if it applies to any provision in ss. 79, 82 or 85 that is integral to the calculation of interest</TI>
<P>50. Paragraph 79(7)(a) provides a deemed definition of tax payable. Therefore, it applies where tax payable is relevant to the calculation of interest. None of the provisions that require a corporation to pay interest (<EM>e.g.</EM>, s. 79(1)), or that allow interest to a corporation refer to tax payable (<EM>i.e.</EM>, ss. 82(4) and 83(1)). The only way s. 79(7)(a) works is if it applies to <BOLD>any</BOLD> provision that is integral to the calculation of interest, even if it does not provide the complete mathematical procedure for working out an amount of interest.</P>
<P>51. In ss. 79, 82 and 83, there are few references to tax payable. Section 79 refers to tax payable only in determining whether a corporation has a deficiency in its tax account, under s. 79(2). The <BOLD>only</BOLD> reference to tax payable in section 82 is in s. 82(5). In defining surplus in a tax account, s. 82(7) refers us back to s. 79(2), which itself refers to tax payable. Section 83 does not refer to tax payable at all.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>4)</N><TI>The other provisions to which s. 79(7) applies also do not contain complete or self-contained mathematical procedures</TI>
<P>52. Subsection 79(7) also applies to the determination of amounts of penalties under ss. 76(1) and (2) and tax payable under ss. 78(4) and (6). Like ss. 79, 82 and 83, these four subsections do not contain complete mathematical procedures.</P>
<BLOCK5><N>a)</N><TI>Late-filing penalties under s. 76(1) and (2)</TI>
<P>53. These two provisions impose penalties for the late filing of an income tax return under the CTA. Subsection 76(1) applies a penalty for failing to file a return on a timely basis for the first time. Subsection 76(2) applies a penalty for repeated failures to file.</P>
<P>54. Each of these subsections sets out a mathematical procedure for calculating a penalty, even using the word &ldquo;formula&rdquo;:
<P1>a) In subsection (1): &ldquo;Every corporation ... is liable to a penalty in the amount calculated using the formula ...&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>b) In subsection (2): &ldquo;Every corporation ... is liable to a penalty determined in accordance with the following formula ...&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>55. As with ss. 79, 82 and 83, even these formulas for calculating penalties are incomplete. The penalties are based on the deficiency in the corporation's tax account. Subsections 76(1) and (2) do not tell us how to calculate the deficiency. We need to look at s. 79(2). Under s. 79(2)(a), one element of this deficiency is the tax payable by the corporation.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N>b)</N><TI>Dispensing with instalments under ss. 78(4) and (6)</TI>
<P>56. Corporations are required to pay instalments toward their tax liability over the course of a taxation year. These two subsections allow corporations with less than $2,000 in tax payable for the year to dispense with paying instalments. Instead, they may pay a single lump sum toward their tax payable.</P>
<P>57. Subsection 78(4) does not itself contain a mathematical procedure. Subsection 78(6) does provide mathematical procedures, but they are not self-contained.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>5)</N><TI>Conclusion on context</TI>
<P>58. The context gives meaning to the phrase &ldquo;for the purposes of calculating interest&rdquo;. Each of ss. 79, 82 and 83 provides part of the mathematical procedure for working out an amount of interest, but none of them, nor any of their individual subsections, can be used in isolation. This shows that s. 82(5), which provides part of this mathematical procedure, is for the purposes of calculating interest.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>THE PURPOSE OF S. 79(7)(a) DOES NOT PREVENT THE DEEMED DEFINTION OF TAX PAYABLE FROM APPLYING TO S. 82(5)</TI>
<P>59. There is nothing in the rationale behind s. 79(7) that prevents the deemed definition of tax payable from applying to any provision that is integral to the calculation of interest, including s. 82(5). The legislative history of s. 79(7) also suggests that the Legislature intended to apply the deemed definition to s. 82(5).</P>
<BLOCK4><N>1)</N><TI>The rationales behind s. 79(7)</TI>
<P>60. The purpose of s. 79(7)(a) is to disregard a loss carryback for interest, penalty and certain payment calculation purposes. The purpose of s. 79(7)(b) is to recognize the loss carryback but only at a later date, and only in certain contexts.</P>
<P>61. The combined effect of ss. 79(7)(a) and (b) is that, for the calculation of interest on the surplus or deficiency in the corporation's tax account, a loss carryback does not change tax payable for a taxation year, but from the effective interest date may reduce tax payable for that taxation year.</P>
<P>62. There is a reason that loss carrybacks are not immediately taken into account in calculating interest. The loss carrybacks arise from expenses that, from the perspective of the taxation year to which they are being applied, arise in the future. As the Federal Court has pointed out, in dealing with the federal counterpart to s. 79(7), the corporation should not be able to refuse to pay tax owing for the year in the hope or expectation that it has a loss to carry back to that year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For interest payable to the taxpayer: s. 164(5), as it currently reads. For interest payable by the taxpayer: s. 161(7), as it currently reads. <CASEREF><SOC>Connaught Laboratories Ltd v R</SOC><CITE>[1994] FCJ no 1681</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM><COURTJUR>TD</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This rationale gives meaning to both ss. 79(7)(a) and (b). The above rationale also applies to the non-recognition of loss carrybacks for the purposes of applying penalties.</P>
<P>63. But s. 79(7)(a) also stands on its own. There are situations in which s. 79(7)(b) is not relevant:
<P1>a) Under ss. 76(1) and (2), a loss carryback is not ever recognized in the computation of a penalty.</P1>
<P1>b) Paragraph 79(7)(b) has no role in the calculation of interest on the surplus or deficiency in an instalment account. The effective interest date arises <BOLD>after</BOLD> interest in the instalment account stops accruing. Interest on the instalment account is payable only during the corporation's instalment period: s. 79(4). Under s. 79(3)(c), the instalment period begins on the first day of the taxation year and ends on the day the balance of the tax payable must be paid under s. 78(2)(b) (either two or three months after the end of the taxation year). The earliest effective interest day is the day after the end of the loss year.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2)</N><TI>Subsection 79(7) evolved to apply to s. 82(5)</TI>
<P>64. The legislative history of ss. 79(7) and 82(5) suggests that the deemed definition of tax payable was intended to apply to s. 82(5). The predecessors of s. 79(7) applied only to the predecessors of s. 82(4). In 1994, a predecessor of s. 79(7) began to refer to <BOLD>all</BOLD> of s. 82.</P>
<P>65. When Ontario took over the administration of its corporate income tax regime in 1957, the Legislature introduced two predecessors to s. 79(7). One was found in s. 73(6) of the Act and dealt with interest <BOLD>allowed</BOLD> to the corporation:
<QUOTE><P>Where a corporation is entitled to deduct under section 37 in computing its taxable income for a taxation year an amount in respect of a loss sustained in the fiscal year immediately following the taxation year, hereinafter in this subsection referred to as &ldquo;the loss year&rdquo;, and the amount of the tax payable for the taxation year is relevant in determining an overpayment for the purpose of computing interest under subsection 3 for any portion of a period ending on or before the last day of the loss year, the tax payable for the taxation year shall be deemed to be the amount that it would have been if the corporation were not entitled to deduct any amount under section 37 in respect of that loss.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Corporations Tax Act, 1957</EM>, SO 1957, c. 17, s. 73(6).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. The reference to subsection 3 is to s. 73(3), the provision that provided the corporation with the general interest rate.</P>
<P>67. An &ldquo;overpayment&rdquo; was defined in s. 73(5) as all amounts paid on account of tax payable for a fiscal year minus all amounts payable under the Act.</P>
<P>68. The other predecessor of s. 79(7) was found in s. 70(5). This provision dealt with interest payable by a corporation. It read as follows:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(5)</N><SSECP>Where a corporation is entitled to deduct under section 37 in computing its taxable income for a taxation year an amount in respect of a loss sustained in the fiscal year immediately following the taxation year, hereinafter in this subsection referred to as &ldquo;the loss year&rdquo;, for the purpose of computing interest and penalty interest under this section on tax or a part or instalment of tax for the taxation year for any portion of the period in respect of which the interest is payable on or before the last day of the loss year, the tax payable for the taxation year shall be deemed to be the amount that it would have been if the corporation were not entitled to deduct any amount under section 37 in respect of that loss.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>69. At the same time, the Legislature introduced the predecessor of s. 82(5), providing for an enhanced rate of interest on successful objections or appeals (paying 6% rather than 3%).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Corporations Tax Act, 1957</EM>, SO 1957, c. 17, s. 73(4).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It included this provision in s. 73(4), the same section in which the loss carryback provision for interest allowed was found.</P>
<P>70. From 1957 through the early 1990s, the CTA had provisions substantially similar to those in s. 73 of the 1957 version of the Act although the interest rates were moved out of the Act into the regulations (and although the Legislature had at one time modified the regulations to apply the general interest rate even to successful objections and appeals<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See RRO 1990, Reg. 183, s. 503 as originally enacted.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>).</P>
<P>71. In the RSO 1990 version of the CTA,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Corporations Tax Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. C.40, as it read upon enactment.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> s. 79 dealt with interest payable by a corporation and s. 82 dealt with interest allowable on overpayments. Subsection 82(5) already contained the enhanced interest rate provision.</P>
<P>72. As with the 1957 CTA, both ss. 79 and 82 contained provisions that were substantially similar to current s. 79(7). Subsection 79(7) dealt with interest payable by the corporation and s. 82(9) with interest allowable by the Minister.</P>
<P>73. Also, as with the 1957 CTA, s., 82(9) referred <BOLD>only</BOLD> to the general interest rate provision&mdash;that is, the equivalent of today's s. 82(4). Subsection 82(9) read as follows:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(9)</N><SSECP>Where a corporation is entitled to carry-back of loss deduct under subsection 111 (1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada) as made applicable by section 34 of this Act in computing its taxable income for a taxation year an amount in respect of a loss sustained in a taxation year following the taxation year, hereinafter in this subsection referred to as &ldquo;the loss year&rdquo;, and the amount of the tax payable for the taxation year is relevant in determining an overpayment for the purpose of computing interest <BOLD>under subsection (4)</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In the RSO 1990 version as enacted, s. 82(4) read:
<QUOTE><P>Where an overpayment is refunded or applied under this section on other liability, interest at such rate as is prescribed by the regulations shall be paid or applied thereon for the period commencing with the later of,
<P1>(a) the day on which the overpayment arose; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the day on or before which the balance of the tax payable for the taxation year is required to be paid pursuant to clause 78 (2) (b),</P1>
and ending with the day of refunding or application aforesaid, unless the amount of the interest so calculated is less than $1, in which event no interest shall be paid or applied under this subsection.</P></QUOTE></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> for any portion of a period ending on or before the last day of the loss year, the tax payable for the taxation year shall be deemed to be the amount that it would have been if the corporation were not entitled to deduct an amount under subsection 111 (1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada) as made applicable by section 34 of this Act in respect of that loss. [Emphasis ours.]</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>74. In 1994 the Legislature amended the CTA to leave the loss carryback provision in s. 79, which still dealt almost entirely with interest payable by the corporation, to remove the loss carryback provision from s. 82, and to keep the enhanced interest rate provision in s. 82(5). It did this, by introducing new s. 79(7) which now covered <BOLD>both</BOLD> interest payable by the corporation and allowed by the Minister:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(7)</N><SSECP>For the purposes of calculating interest payable or allowed under this section or section 82 or 83 in respect of a particular taxation year, and for the purpose of determining the amount of a penalty, if any, to be assessed under subsection 76 (1),
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>the tax payable by the corporation under this Act for a taxation year shall be deemed to be the amount that would otherwise be determined if all amounts deducted by the corporation for that year under section 111 of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> (Canada), as it applies for the purposes of this Act, in respect of a loss for a taxation year after the particular year (in this section referred to as the &ldquo;loss year&rdquo;) were not deducted; and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the amount, if any, by which the tax payable by the corporation under this Act for the particular taxation year is reduced as a result of a deduction referred to in clause (a) shall be deemed to be an amount paid by the corporation on account of its liability under this Act for the particular year on the day that is the latest of,
<SPARA><N>(i)</N><SPARAP>the first day of the taxation year after the loss year,</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(ii)</N><SPARAP>the day on which the corporation's return for the loss year is delivered to the Minister, or</SPARAP></SPARA>
<SPARA><N>(iii)</N><SPARAP>the day on which the Minister receives a request in writing from the corporation to reassess the particular taxation year to take into account the deduction referred to in clause (a).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Corporations Tax Amendment Act, 1994</EM>, SO 1994, c. 14, s. 37(3).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>75. At the same time, the Legislature enacted s. 82(5) in more or less its current form:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(5)</N><SSECP>Where, by a decision made under section 84 or 92 or by a court, it is finally determined that the tax payable under this Act by a corporation for a taxation year is less than the amount assessed under section 80 to which the objection was made or from which the appeal was taken, and as a result of the decision there is a surplus in the corporation's tax account for a taxation year or in the corporation's instalment account for a taxation year, the interest rate prescribed by the regulations for the purposes of this subsection, and not the rate prescribed for the purposes of subsection (4) or 83 (1), as the case may be, shall be used to determine the amount of interest for the purposes of those subsections, for each day that the surplus in the account is attributable to the decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Corporations Tax Amendment Act, 1994</EM>, SO 1994, c. 14, s. 40(3).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>76. This history shows that the Legislature moved from a loss carryback provision that targeted the ordinary interest provision (the counterpart to today's s. 82(4)) to one that applied to the whole of s. 82, encompassing s. 82(5), the provision on which the Appellant wants to rely.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The references to ss. 78(4) and (6) were added by SO 1996, c. 29, s. 61(4), deemed to have come into force on February 28, 1995 (per s. 65(17)). The reference to s. 76(2) was added by SO 2002, c. 22, s. 53(2).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It suggests that the Legislature intended that deemed definition of tax payable apply to s. 82(5).</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>F.</N><TI>THE APPLICATION OF S. 79(7)(a) TO S. 82(5)</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>1)</N><TI>Subsection 82(5) is for the purposes of calculating interest</TI>
<P>77. The Appellant suggests that s. 82(5) determines only entitlement to the enhanced interest rate, and is not about calculating interest. However, s. 82(5) is for the purposes of interest calculation. Since s. 82(5) is for the purposes of calculating interest, s. 79(7)(a)'s definition of tax payable applies to it and denies the Appellant the enhanced interest rate.</P>
<P>78. Interpreted in light of its text, context and purpose, s. 79(7)(a) does not require th at a particular provision contain the entire mathematical procedure for working out an amount interest before the deemed definition of tax payable will apply to it. It is enough that the provision be integral to this procedure.</P>
<P>79. In order to calculate interest under s. 82(4) where a corporation has successfully objected to or appealed from an assessment, we must look at another provision. Subsection 82(4) does not tell us the relevant interest rate that we must use, nor does it tell us the part of the surplus that we are to apply this interest rate. Subsection 82(5) gives us this missing information.</P>
<P>80. Subsection 82(5) provides integral parts of the mathematical procedure for the calculation of interest allowable on a surplus in the corporation's tax or instalment accounts, after a successful objection or appeal. It provides:
<P1>a) the principal amount&mdash;the part of the surplus to which the enhanced interest rate is applied. Not all surplus balances in a corporation's instalment and tax accounts on a given day are eligible for the enhanced interest rate. Only the portion of the surplus balance that is attributable to the decision on objection or appeal on that day is eligible for the enhanced rate;</P1>
<P1>b) the interest rate; and</P1>
<P1>c) the time when this interest rate is to be applied to the principal amount&mdash;daily.</P1></P>
<P>81. Given the role of s. 82(5), the deemed definition of tax payable in s. 79(7)(a) applies to s. 82(5).</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>2)</N><TI>The purpose of s. 82(5) does not justify departing from the s. 79(7) deemed definition of tax payable</TI>
<P>82. The Appellant repeatedly suggests that the intention behind s. 82(5) is to punish the Minister for a wrong; that wrong being the denial of the non -capital loss carryback. The notion that the Minister is to be punished for a successful objection should not drive the understanding of the interaction between ss. 79(7) and 82(5).</P>
<P>83. There is no enhanced rate of interest under the Federal Act where a taxpayer is successful on an objection or appeal.</P>
<P>84. The rationale for enhanced interest is set out in the Ontario Committee on Taxation's 1967 report:
<P1>a) If the taxpayer and the government agree on the amount to be refunded, interest should be below current borrowing rates to prevent the taxpayer from using the government as a savings deposit bank, and</P1>
<P1>b) If the taxpayer is successful after a dispute over taxes with the government, it should receive interest comparable to market rates.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ontario, Ontario Committee on Taxation, <EM>Report</EM>, vol. Ill (1967), at pp 14-15, paras 20-21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>85. In light of these comments, s. 79(7)(a) should not be interpreted to allow the Minister to be punished under s. 82(5). The purpose of s. 82(5) is not punishment.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>3)</N><TI>Despite s. 79(7)(a), the Appellant does receive compensation for the use of its money</TI>
<P>86. The Appellant suggests that, if s. 79(7) applies, the Minister is allowed to hold onto an overpayment with impunity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Factum of the Appellant, para 40(a).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is not the case.</P>
<P>87. While the effect of s. 79(7)(a) is that the Appellant does not get the enhanced rate of interest for the loss carryback, the Appellant may still get interest at the general rate.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In some years, though, the general interest rate was nil. See Ontario&mdash;Prescribed Interest Rates, 1&mdash;Ontario Ministry of Finance Interest Rates, as of April 1, 2019 (from v3.taxnetpro.com, accessed May 14, 2019).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>88. Here the effective interest date is June 25, 2010, the day on which the Appellant delivered its return for the 2010 Year (the loss year) to the Minister.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Partial Agreed Statement of Facts, para 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On that day, pursuant to s. 79(7)(b), the loss carryback was deemed a payment toward the Appellant's tax payable (before the application of the loss carryback). If on that date, the payment generated a surplus&mdash;<EM>i.e.</EM>, put simply, if the amounts paid or deemed paid by the Appellant exceeded the amounts payable by it&mdash;the Appellant would obtain interest at the general rate prescribed for s. 82(4).</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>4)</N><TI>Conclusion on purpose</TI>
<P>89. There are two policies in the CTA. One is to provide an enhanced rate of interest after a decision on an objection or appeal reduces tax payable. Another is to calculate tax payable without taking into account, or at least deferring recognition, of loss carrybacks in interest, penalty, and certain payment calculations.</P>
<P>90. The text and context of s. 79(7) have resolved any competition between these policies. Where a provision is for the purposes of calculating interest, tax payable is deemed to be tax payable without taking into account a loss carryback. Because there is no one provision in ss. 79, 82, and 83 that provides a complete mathematical procedure for calculating interest, any provision in ss. 79, 82 and 83 that is integral to the calculation of interest is also for the purposes of calculating interest. A provision integral to the calculation of interest is one that provides the principal amount on which the interest is to be calculated, the interest rate, or the time over which the interest accrues.</P>
<P>91. Subsection 82(5) is an integral provision. In applying s. 82(5), tax payable is deemed to mean tax payable without taking into account the loss carryback.</P>
<P>92. As a result, for interest calculation purposes, there was no difference between the tax payable for the 2008 Year as first reassessed by the Minister, which resulted from the denial of the loss carryback from the 2010 Year, and the tax payable by the Appellant after the decision on the objection, which resulted from reinstating the loss carryback. The enhanced interest rate in s. 82(5) does not apply.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">IV. ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>93. The answer is &ldquo;No&rdquo; to the Appellant's question whether, in determining a corporation's entitlement to an enhanced refund interest rate under s. 82(5) of the CTA, tax payable must take a deduction from a loss carried back into account. That is, s. 79(7)(a)'s deemed definition of tax payable applies to s. 82(5) and tax payable is the corporation's tax payable before the application of a loss carryback.</P>
<P>94. Costs should be awarded to the Respondent.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</P>
<P>Dated at Toronto, Ontario this 15<SUP>th</SUP> day of May 2019.</P>
